text.__SUMMARY__: Eucalyptus sporadica (Burngup mallee) is a mallee that is native to a large area in south western Western Australia.
text.Description: The bark is smooth and red-brown, grey greenish grey or silvery white, but occasionally there is a short rough stocking. There is glandular pith in the branchlets. The juvenile leaves are petiolate and alternate and a light green to bluish green. The petiolate adult leaves are concolorous and a glossy green and lanceolate or falcate of length 5-9 x 1-1.8 cm.  The inflorescences are axillary and seven flowered on a downcurved peduncle. The buds are elongated. The flowers are white and seen from May to September. The anthers are all fertile. The fruit is cylindrical and the valves are exserted.  It grows on sand, loam, clay soils and gravel and is found on granite outcrops, lateritic hills and breakaways.
text.Distribution: It is found in the IBRA Regions: Avon Wheatbelt, Coolgardie, Esperance Plains, Mallee, Murchison.
